					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">Okay, so let's go with what you said and interp_index is 15 bits and the upper 3 bits can have any value from 0&lt;=i&lt;=7.  If that is the case then the code directly below the interp_index &gt;&gt; 12 is confusing for how it indexes BRRdata[]...<br /><div class="codetitle"><b>Code:</b></div><div class="codecontent">&nbsp; &nbsp; outx&nbsp; = ((gauss&#91;255-d&#93; * voice&#91;x&#93;.BRRdata&#91;i+0&#93;) &gt;&gt; 11);<br />&nbsp; &nbsp; outx += ((gauss&#91;511-d&#93; * voice&#91;x&#93;.BRRdata&#91;i+1&#93;) &gt;&gt; 11);<br />&nbsp; &nbsp; outx += ((gauss&#91;256+d&#93; * voice&#91;x&#93;.BRRdata&#91;i+2&#93;) &gt;&gt; 11);<br />&nbsp; &nbsp; // The above 3 wrap at 15 bits signed. The last is added to that, and is<br />&nbsp; &nbsp; // clamped rather than wrapped.<br />&nbsp; &nbsp; outx = ((outx &amp; 0x7FFF) ^ 0x4000) - 0x4000;<br />&nbsp; &nbsp; outx += ((gauss&#91;&nbsp; 0+d&#93; * voice&#91;x&#93;.BRRdata&#91;i+3&#93;) &gt;&gt; 11);</div><br />In that block it uses 'i' to index any one of BRRdata[i+0] through BRRdata[i+3]. In that case the highest index achievable would only be BRRdata[10]. Which is confusing since the ring buffer holds 12 samples at any time. So indexes 11 and 12 are never used?<br /><br />Oddly, it actually made more sense when 'i' ranged from 0&lt;=i&lt;=4 since that would allow indexing BRRdata with any index from BRRdata[0] through BRRdata[7]. I was thinking that kind of made more sense since Anomie describes the ring buffer as having only 2 &quot;active&quot; groups (of 4 samples each). So 0&lt;=i&lt;=4 would allow you to reference any of the 8 &quot;active&quot; samples.</div>

