						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">Okay, so let's go with what you said and interp_index is 15 bits and the upper 3 bits can have any value from 0&lt;=i&lt;=7.</div><br />An assertion added to Spc_Dsp::interpolate() shows that it does go greater than 4. It fails when run through my DSP test suite:<br /><div class="codetitle"><b>Code:</b></div><div class="codecontent">inline int Spc_Dsp::interpolate( voice_t const* v )<br />{<br />&nbsp; &nbsp;...<br />&nbsp; &nbsp;assert( (v-&gt;interp_pos &gt;&gt; 12) &lt;= 4 ); // this fails<br />&nbsp; &nbsp;int const* in = &amp;v-&gt;buf &#91;(v-&gt;interp_pos &gt;&gt; 12) + v-&gt;buf_pos&#93;;<br /></div><br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent"><div class="codetitle"><b>Code:</b></div><div class="codecontent">outx += ((gauss&#91;&nbsp; 0+d&#93; * voice&#91;x&#93;.BRRdata&#91;i+3&#93;) &gt;&gt; 11);</div><br />In that block it uses 'i' to index any one of BRRdata[i+0] through BRRdata[i+3]. In that case the highest index achievable would only be BRRdata[10]. Which is confusing since the ring buffer holds 12 samples at any time. So indexes 11 and 12 are never used?</div><br />The indicies are 0-11, and the above can only touch 0-10, so it can't touch the last entry. But it's a ring buffer, so that's just on this round; once it's shifted forward four samples, it will be able to reach the former 12th entry.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">Oddly, it actually made more sense when 'i' ranged from 0&lt;=i&lt;=4 since that would allow indexing BRRdata with any index from BRRdata[0] through BRRdata[7]. I was thinking that kind of made more sense since Anomie describes the ring buffer as having only 2 &quot;active&quot; groups (of 4 samples each). So 0&lt;=i&lt;=4 would allow you to reference any of the 8 &quot;active&quot; samples.</div><br />I don't think that was written when it was known that the interpolation position could move so far ahead of normal.</div>

